snippet.textDisplay:
Series X won't be more expensive. I love people talking nonsense, tbh. If you understood what the PS5 tries to do, then you know it can't be compared to Xbox and viceversa.
Wich is better now? Well, we don't know. But "on paper" PS5 doesn't need a 12 tflops GPU to produce the same results. XSX can run a huge texture and geometry load at stable framerate and 4K resolution, while PS5 can load and release those assets as they enter in the player's field of view(it doesn't need to load everything surrounding, hence freeing the gpu) thanks to the speed of the SSD and it's controller.
It's easy: the money Xbox espent on the GPU, Sony used it for the SSD. Two very different aproaches. Both consoles are gonna be $499.
Comparing XSX and PS5 on paper is like comparing Xbox 360 and PS3. You can't.
Series X is more PC like, friendly and straightforward, just like Xbox 360; while PS5 a little more unique, specific and "weird", just like the PS3.
The diference is that, unlike PS3, Sony's new machine is very developer friendly.
So yeah, for people who like tech these are very exciting times! The PS4/XONE gen was a mess: weak machines and really poor tech. You could compare teraflops with these because they literally were the same machine.
Comparing teraflops for Next Gen is like comparing teraflops in orange and apples: 1 tflop for Series X isn't the same as 1 tflop for PS5.
PS: sorry for my english, i tried to explain the best i could.

From hardware to software, Microsoft seems to be taking the gaming market seriously in an attempt to increase market share (even though Sony depends more on Playstation revenue where over 20% of Sony revenue comes from Playstation and PSN).  Corporate investment in the cloud and PC environment will only strengthen Microsoft in the long run.
